\cf0\ul At the Presbytery Offices\par
\par
\ulnone As was his habit, Aaron Muis took out a new manila folder and carefully labeled it 'Deem Futz', going back and forth three times due to the spelling.  Into the crisp new folder went a piece of lined paper with the date, June 16, 2016, at the top. He carefully wrote 'bishop assigned me candidate shepherding, this pastoral candidate to Nicholls Epper Church.'  He thought a moment, looked at his watch, and noted the time : 10:04 AM. \par
\par
"You'll be picking him up from the bus station. The candidate will be arriving by bus from Michigan. I realize it is short notice, but he should be there at 5:00 this afternoon. I apologize for the short notice."\par
\par
"The Greyhound station?"\par
\par
"Is there another? It's KC-Mo.  Not the one over in KC-K.""\par
\par
"I was thinking maybe Lee's Summit.  But maybe I'm thinking of Amtrak. Downtown KC-MO it is."   Hearing that, Aaron turned to the photograph, on top of the pile of papers: the administrator's checklist certifying the papers were in order, and in the proper order his application, resume, reccommendations, transcripts, etc.   He slid all these papers into the folder.\par
\par
Aaron frowned at the picture.  Was it blank?  No.  There was a face, but he could not get a focus on it.  The most unremarkable, unnoticable face he'd ever seen. It told him nothing, absolutely nothing except the candidate had a nose, two eyes, a mouth, ears.  Maybe. They were hard to get a fix on or even describe, beyond that difficulty. What  he could see was something that told him nothing.  He noted this on a new line of his lined piece of paper, and returned to the photograph, which again seemed to be blank for a moment until he figured out how to find the face.  If Aaron put his finger on the nose, then he could see it.  But he had to look twice.\par
\par

\pard\ltrpar\sa200\sl276\slmult1\lang9 Aaron had been told Deem was like that in person: forgettable, without impression. People walked into him without noticing him.  In one of the classes where attendence had been taken, a professor had stared at his seat in silence. "Ah, there you are," he had finally said. There was something about him that made him almost invisible, unnoticable.  The guy could walk into a bank and rob it, and no one would notice. No one would be able to describe this man with the super power of invisibility.\f1\par
Aaron then skimmed the resume, the letters concerning the subject, the transcript and other data that had been assembled, including the application, closed the manila folder and placed it before him on the mahogany desk, which was clear of everything except the interwoven fingers of the man opposite him. The only thing he had read carefully was the letter of recommendation from the man opposite him now, which was more faint praise than enthusiasm. "And you think he is the right fit for Nicholls. sir?" Aaron asked the bishop, who had been watching him this whole time.  The bishop had said he wanted to watch Aaron's face as he read through things, not have Aaron go off to his office, think it through and then report.  He wanted his initial reaction.  Reflection would come later. \par
"It may be more that Nicholls is the right fit for him.  I know this Deem Futz.  Never has anyone had more trouble, more grief, more anguish, yet remained alive and managed to finish seminary."\par
"Perhaps he invites trouble.  Why should he bring trouble to Nicholls?  Though if any place deserves it - excuse me.  He was the goat of his class. There has not been a goat in fifty years, and here he is."\par
"An unfortunate phrase, an antique phrase, one that I would not like to see used again. Let us say that he managed to pass all his courses with a minimal amount of margin?"\par
"Let us so say.  For lack of payment he was almost expelled three times."\par
"Yet the finances came through."\par
"Sometimes late. Past the limit. It was only the mercy of the seminary president himself that accepted the payments."\par
"But there it is.  Mercy.  The payment was made.  Some would prefer to have someone as a pastor who has been through what Deem has been through than someone who has never been touched by the fire.  And here he is, despite forty-six - count them - forty-six interviews, some of whom told him they would wait for next year rather than accepting him. Incredible.  And he has not given up."\par
"He was brought up on disciplinary charges. Conduct unbecoming a seminary student."\par
"And he was cleared.  I was on the board that cleared him on one of those occaisions.  It seemed to us he had been framed, almost supernaturally, if you will. Do recall I was in Michigan at the time, and I served on several of the review boards that allowed him to remain in seminary."\par
"He has watched every other student in his class placed, years behind his starting class, and he is the last one."\par
"Yet he perseveres."\par
"A rational man would say that God was calling him to do something else."\par

