\par
\cf0 "I must say, Candidate Futz, that I admire your determination, your perseverance. Despite everything you have been through, it does not seem to have fazed you."\cf1\par
\par
\cf0 "Thank you, Deacon Muis.  I regard it as training - the same thing that made Naomi bitter made Ruth better.  And Naomi, as I am sure you know, turned her name meaning 'Pleasantness' to Mara, meaning bitter.  I see it as a choice.  Not that I have always made the right one, but I do try to keep that in mind.  And Romans 5. And 2 Peter 1. I try to hold those close to my heart."\par
\par
"Many say that, but few live it as I think you do."\par
\par
"God has not allowed me much choice, now, has He?"\par
\par
"You always had a choice.  And I understand you always made the right one."\par
\par
Deem said nothing.  The bishop smiled and nodded.  Aaron also had made the right choice, here, and had said the right thing.  If he had not been such a political animal he could have taken the words to heart, but instead he considered this conversation in terms of how it would advance his own position, and safeguard himself in case something went wrong with one of the other two men.  Aaron thought in terms of alliances, strategies and tactics, and how to advance his own interests.  \par
\par
The bishop sat there wondering if this conversation had gotten through to Aaron, or if his armor was simply too thick.  He now believed the warnings he had heard about having to watch Aaron Muis, and eventually something would have to be done.  But he had no one else to take Deem Futz to Nicholls, no one knew the town as well, and certainly no one wanted to tangle with that situation. How could a man say such things and sound so hollow?  \par
